        output='Based on the provided financial excerpts, here is a summary of the disclosures regarding SpaceX\'s Space segment R&D breakdown and its impact on operating results:\n\n### **Breakdown of Space Segment R&D between Starship and Other Programs**\nThe filings consistently state that the **Space segment\'s R&D expenses "mainly relate to the development, build, and testing of Starship."** While a precise percentage split between Starship and other R&D is not given, the context and financial drivers clearly indicate that **Starship is the dominant and primary focus** of the segment\'s R&D spending.\n\n*   **Primary Component:** The documents list the core components of Starship R&D costs as:\n    *   Test flight hardware and Raptor engines\n    *   Employee compensation\n    *   Tooling and equipment\n    *   Depreciation for R&D equipment\n    *   Allocated overhead\n    *   Development of production and launch facilities to support Starship.\n*   **Other R&D:** There is a minor mention that R&D also includes "certain expenses related to the development of features and modules created through engineering services for the Company’s Falcon vehicles," where the company retains the rights. This appears to be a relatively small component compared to the massive Starship program.\n\n**In essence, while not quantified, the disclosures frame Starship as the overwhelming driver of the Space segment\'s R&D budget.**\n\n### **Relationship of Starship R&D to Segment Operating Results**\nThe filings directly and repeatedly attribute the **Space segment\'s operating losses and declining EBITDA to the accelerated investment in Starship development.**\n\n1.  **Direct Cause of Losses:** Multiple sections state that the increased loss from operations and decreased Segment Adjusted EBITDA are "primarily driven by an accelerated investment in development of the Starship vehicle as well as launch facilities."\n    *   **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:** The Space segment\'s operating loss increased by **$592 million** (to $(662) million), primarily due to this investment.\n    *   **FY 2025 vs. FY 2024:** The Space segment\'s Adjusted EBITDA decreased by **$501 million** (to $653 million) for the same reason.\n\n2.  **Magnitude of Investment:** The financial data highlights the scale of the bet:\n    *   **2024:** $1,835 million in Space R&D.\n    *   **2025:** $3,004 million in Space R&D (a 64% increase year-over-year).\n    *   **Q1 2026:** $930 million in Space R&D (annualized pace of ~$3.7B).\n\n3.  **Future Outlook and Capitalization:** The company explicitly frames this as a strategic, multi-year investment with a future payoff:\n    *   It expects Space R&D "to increase both in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue in 2026."\n    *   It states that these costs will **"moderate both in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue once Starship is commercialized."**\n    *   Crucially, **at commercialization, Starship costs will shift from being expensed as R&D to being capitalized as property and depreciated in cost of revenue.** This accounting change will dramatically improve the segment\'s reported operating metrics.\n\n### **Summary of Disclosures**\nIn conclusion, the financial disclosures clearly show that:\n*   The vast majority of Space segment R&D is for **Starship development**.\n*   This massive investment is the **direct and primary cause** of the segment\'s recent operating losses and negative Adjusted EBITDA.\n*   The company presents this not as a failed cost, but as a **deliberate, front-loaded investment** to achieve technological leadership. The current financial "losses" are expected to be temporary, pending Starship\'s commercialization, at which point the cost structure will fundamentally change.',
