        output='Based on the precise wording in the filing, the **$3,004 million figure represents R&D expense *specifically for the Starship launch vehicle program***, not the total Space segment R&D.\n\nHere are the key quotes that establish this:\n\n1.  **Direct Attribution:** The most definitive statement appears multiple times:\n    > "Additionally, our Space segment funded $930 million and **$3,004 million in research and development expense** during the three months ended March 31, 2026 and the year ended December 31, 2025, **respectively, for our next-generation Starship launch vehicle program.**"\n\n    The phrase "for our next-generation Starship launch vehicle program" directly modifies the R&D expense amount, indicating the purpose and scope of that specific expenditure.\n\n2.  **Causal Link in MD&A:** In the "Results of Operations" analysis, the increase in Space segment R&D is directly tied to Starship:\n    > "Research and development for the year ended December 31, 2025 increased by $1,169 million... This increase was primarily driven by higher production costs of $779 million, higher launch costs of $218 million, and higher engineering costs of $185 million, **due to the accelerated investment in development of the Starship vehicle**..."\n\n3.  **Capital Allocation Context:** The filing consistently uses the $3,004 million figure as a key metric for Starship investment when discussing the company\'s strategy and capital allocation:\n    > "For example, in 2025 we accelerated our timeline for Starship development, **increasing R&D in our Space segment to $3,004 million**, compared to $1,835 million in 2024."\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nThe filing is precise in its language. It does **not** state that the $3,004 million is "total Space segment R&D that mainly relates to Starship." Instead, it explicitly attributes this sum **as the R&D expense "for" the Starship program**. This indicates that the reported figure is the amount funded by the Space segment specifically for Starship development activities. Other, likely smaller, R&D efforts within the Space segment (such as for Falcon or Dragon) would be accounted for separately or within other line items.',
